ManSection.Description:
        S is a numerical semigroup and E is an ideal of S with E\subseteq S.
        The output is S\bowtie E= D\cup (E\times E)\cup\{ a\wedge b\mid a\in D, b\in E\times E\}, where D=\{(s,s)\mid s\in S\}.


gap> s:=NumericalSemigroup(3,5,7);;
gap> e:=6+s;;
gap> dup:=NumericalSemigroupDuplication(s,e);
<Good semigroup>
gap> l:=Cartesian([1..11],[1..11]);;
gap> Intersection(dup,l);
[ [ 3, 3 ], [ 5, 5 ], [ 6, 6 ], [ 6, 7 ], [ 6, 8 ], [ 6, 9 ], [ 6, 10 ], 
  [ 6, 11 ], [ 7, 6 ], [ 7, 7 ], [ 8, 6 ], [ 8, 8 ], [ 9, 6 ], [ 9, 9 ], 
  [ 9, 10 ], [ 9, 11 ], [ 10, 6 ], [ 10, 9 ], [ 10, 10 ], [ 11, 6 ], 
  [ 11, 9 ], [ 11, 11 ] ]
gap> [384938749837,349823749827] in dup;
true

          S is a numerical semigroup, E is an ideal of a numerical semigroup T with E\subseteq T, and b is an integer such that multiplication by b is a morphism from S to T, say g.
          The output is S\bowtie^g E= D\cup(g^{-1}(E)\times E)\cup \{a\wedge b\mid a\in D, b\in g^{-1}(E)\times E\}, where D=\{(s,b s)\mid s\in S\}.


gap> s:=NumericalSemigroup(2,3);;
gap> t:=NumericalSemigroup(3,4);;
gap> e:=3+t;;
gap> dup:=AmalgamationOfNumericalSemigroups(s,e,2);;
gap> [2,3] in dup;
true

          S and T are numerical semigroups.
          The output is S\times T, which is a good semigroup.


gap> s:=NumericalSemigroup(2,3);;
gap> t:=NumericalSemigroup(3,4);;
gap> IsGoodSemigroup(CartesianProductOfNumericalSemigroups(s,t));
true

          X is a list of points with nonnegative integer coordinates and C is a pair of nonnegative integer (a list with two elements).
          If M is the affine and infimum closure of X, decides if it is a good semigroup, and if so, outputs it.


gap> G:=[[4,3],[7,13],[11,17],[14,27],[15,27],[16,20],[25,12],[25,16]];
[ [ 4, 3 ], [ 7, 13 ], [ 11, 17 ], [ 14, 27 ], [ 15, 27 ], [ 16, 20 ], 
  [ 25, 12 ], [ 25, 16 ] ]
gap> C:=[25,27];
[ 25, 27 ]
gap> GoodSemigroup(G,C);
<Good semigroup>

      S is a good semigroup. The output is its conductor.


gap> s:=NumericalSemigroup(3,5,7);;
gap> e:=6+s;;
gap> dup:=NumericalSemigroupDuplication(s,e);
<Good semigroup>
gap> Conductor(dup);
[ 11, 11 ]

      S is a good semigroup. The output is its set of small elements, that is, the elements smaller than its conductor with respect to the usual partial ordering.


